items.content: Hwy
Hey! Did you mean “hey,” or are you asking about a highway? Either way, how can I help?
Both, as a metaphor for desparation

Hey is what I say when I don’t know what to ask,
a small flare thrown into the dusk,
a syllable that hopes someone will pull over.

The highway is a longer word for the same thing:
an endless hand held out, palm of asphalt,
white lines flicking like a heartbeat you’re trying to steady.
Mile markers stand like tally marks—
I was here, I was here, I am still here.

On the overhead sign it’s just HWY,
letters shaved down by wind and budget,
and between hey and hwy there’s a Y
that forks like a question I can’t stop arriving at.
Why am I driving. Why the radio static
knitting a thin sweater around my ribs.
Why the exits named after towns that sound like alibis.

Hey, I whisper into the windshield,
and the glass hands it to the night,
and the night hands it to the ditch,
and the ditch says nothing but cricket.

Headlights ahead are prayers I tailgate
because they’re the only proof of company.
The road is a sentence that forgot its period,
shoulders gathering the grammar of broken bottles,
rest areas lit like patient rooms.

I keep going because the centerline tells me to,
because the speed feels like deciding,
because there is a kind of mercy in motion.
Hey, I say again, and again the world
pretends not to hear—yet still
the highway unspools its dark ribbon,
and I follow, desperate for any knot
that feels like a hand, or a home, or an answer.

items.content: Hwy
Hey! Did you mean “hey,” or are you asking about a highway? Either way, how can I help?
Both, as a metaphor for desparation

Hey is what I say when I don’t know what to ask,
a small flare thrown into the dusk,
a syllable that hopes someone will pull over.

The highway is a longer word for the same thing:
an endless hand held out, palm of asphalt,
white lines flicking like a heartbeat you’re trying to steady.
Mile markers stand like tally marks—
I was here, I was here, I am still here.

On the overhead sign it’s just HWY,
letters shaved down by wind and budget,
and between hey and hwy there’s a Y
that forks like a question I can’t stop arriving at.
Why am I driving. Why the radio static
knitting a thin sweater around my ribs.
Why the exits named after towns that sound like alibis.

Hey, I whisper into the windshield,
and the glass hands it to the night,
and the night hands it to the ditch,
and the ditch says nothing but cricket.

Headlights ahead are prayers I tailgate
because they’re the only proof of company.
The road is a sentence that forgot its period,
shoulders gathering the grammar of broken bottles,
rest areas lit like patient rooms.

I keep going because the centerline tells me to,
because the speed feels like deciding,
because there is a kind of mercy in motion.
Hey, I say again, and again the world
pretends not to hear—yet still
the highway unspools its dark ribbon,
and I follow, desperate for any knot
that feels like a hand, or a home, or an answer.
